—Щearchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/lang-guide/chapters/types/basic_types/table.mdЩ@ae9e48ebf99ab06979ce1eb86677ab2f67268e7a00411cf1fb6d9752363d6dc2ҐTable‘ґTable-literal syntaxЪTable literals can be created using a syntax similar to that of a list literal. Because tables also contain columns and not just values, we also specify the column names:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
[[column1, column2]; [Value1, Value2] [Value3, Value4]]
# => в•­в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв•®
# => в”‚ # в”‚ column1 в”‚ column2 в”‚
# => в”њв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”јв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”јв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¤
# => в”‚ 0 в”‚ Value1  в”‚ Value2  в”‚
# => в”‚ 1 в”‚ Value3  в”‚ Value4  в”‚
# => в•°в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв•Ї

```
In this syntax, the headers are separated from the data cells using a semicolon(
``;``
). The semicolon separator is mandatory in a table-literal. It must follow the headers.
’ђђЪJTitle: Table
Path: Table-literal syntax
Content:
Table literals can be created using a syntax similar to that of a list literal. Because tables also contain columns and not just values, we also specify the column names:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
[[column1, column2]; [Value1, Value2] [Value3, Value4]]
# => в•­в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв•®
# => в”‚ # в”‚ column1 в”‚ column2 в”‚
# => в”њв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”јв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”јв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¤
# => в”‚ 0 в”‚ Value1  в”‚ Value2  в”‚
# => в”‚ 1 в”‚ Value3  в”‚ Value4  в”‚
# => в•°в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв•Ї

```
In this syntax, the headers are separated from the data cells using a semicolon(
``;``
). The semicolon separator is mandatory in a table-literal. It must follow the headers.
—Щearchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/lang-guide/chapters/types/basic_types/table.mdЩ@2f36c4df01670d3b5ed9afc7d93ed6994604e0b55bf4995d372b1a2a2bcf2912ҐTable‘¶List-of-Records syntaxЪ№You can also create a table as a list of records, JSON-style:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
[{name: "Sam", rank: 10}, {name: "Bob", rank: 7}]
# => в•­в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв•®
# => в”‚ # в”‚ name в”‚ rank в”‚
# => в”њв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”јв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”јв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¤
# => в”‚ 0 в”‚ Sam  в”‚   10 в”‚
# => в”‚ 1 в”‚ Bob  в”‚    7 в”‚
# => в•°в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв•Ї

```
This list-of-records pattern plays on the Nushell data model, which sees a list of records as equivalent to a table. This is useful in cases where the length of a table may not be known ahead of time. In such a case, a stream of records likewise represents a table.
’ђђЪмTitle: Table
Path: List-of-Records syntax
Content:
You can also create a table as a list of records, JSON-style:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
[{name: "Sam", rank: 10}, {name: "Bob", rank: 7}]
# => в•­в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв•®
# => в”‚ # в”‚ name в”‚ rank в”‚
# => в”њв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”јв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”јв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¤
# => в”‚ 0 в”‚ Sam  в”‚   10 в”‚
# => в”‚ 1 в”‚ Bob  в”‚    7 в”‚
# => в•°в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв•Ї

```
This list-of-records pattern plays on the Nushell data model, which sees a list of records as equivalent to a table. This is useful in cases where the length of a table may not be known ahead of time. In such a case, a stream of records likewise represents a table.
—Щearchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/lang-guide/chapters/types/basic_types/table.mdЩ@86ad1cb1545b5e794df876adeacdc466c7e133dc516416a24facf3f88fdb048dҐTable‘Щ&Common commands that can be used with Ща``table``
``table``
``ls``
``ps``
``sys``
``select``
``get``
``where``
``range``
::: tip Note

Most of Nushell's filter commands work with tables. For a longer list see: 
``help commands | where category == filters``
.

:::
